{
  "text": "The wide use of oral contraceptives (OC) is based on their reliability. However, OC use is associated with an increased risk of venous and arterial thromboembolic events. [CITATION_1] The majority of which are venous thrombosis events, especially peripheral venous thrombosis. OC-related arterial thromboembolic events are relatively uncommon, and generally comprise cerebral vascular events and ischemic heart diseases. [CITATION_2] The present case report describes a long-term OC user who developed painless myocardial infarction (MI), concomitant with left ventricular (LV) thrombus formation, and multiple arterial embolism.",
